The Book of Transformations

A Field Manual for Pattern Translation

Core idea

A transformation pattern is a repeatable move that takes:
	•	one structure
	•	one state
	•	one framing
	•	one domain

and turns it into another while preserving, revealing, suppressing, or reorganizing invariants.

So each move has:
	•	a name
	•	a glyph
	•	a function
	•	a tensor signature
	•	a use case
	•	a martial instruction

⸻

Part I — The 12 Base Forms

These are your “stances.”

⸻

1. Map

Glyph: →
Move: send one thing into another domain
Function: correspondence, translation, encoding
Tensor signature: (source, target, preserved_features)

What it does

Finds a workable correspondence:
	•	voltage → pressure
	•	memory → terrain
	•	narrative tension → potential energy

Martial instruction

Enter the opponent’s space without becoming the opponent.
Do not carry over everything. Carry only the structure that survives translation.

Use when

You suspect two domains share a skeleton.

Failure mode

False analogy.

⸻

2. Mirror

Glyph: ↔
Move: reflect a system to expose symmetry or inversion
Function: duality, self-check, reverse view
Tensor signature: (system, reflected_system, invariant)

What it does

Shows:
	•	what flips
	•	what stays
	•	what only appears true from one side

Martial instruction

Use the force of the strike to reveal the striker.
When confused, reverse the relation and inspect what survives.

Use when

You want to expose hidden assumptions or dual formulations.

Failure mode

Mistaking aesthetic symmetry for real invariance.

⸻

3. Rotate

Glyph: ⟳
Move: change perspective without changing underlying object
Function: coordinate change, reframing, basis shift
Tensor signature: (object, basis_1, basis_2)

What it does

Turns:
	•	obstacle into constraint
	•	pain into signal
	•	delay into option value
	•	story into system
	•	system into geometry

Martial instruction

Do not push the wall. Turn your body and let the opening appear.

Use when

A problem seems stuck because the current frame is too expensive.

Failure mode

Confusing re-description with actual progress.

⸻

4. Compress

Glyph: ⇣
Move: reduce many details into a shorter invariant package
Function: abstraction, encoding, symbol formation
Tensor signature: (raw_structure, code, recoverable_loss)

What it does

Builds:
	•	symbols
	•	names
	•	archetypes
	•	formulas
	•	summaries
	•	tokens

Martial instruction

Fold the cloak so the whole journey fits in one hand.

Use when

You need portability, memory, speed, or transfer.

Failure mode

Overcompression; meaning collapses into mush.

⸻

5. Expand

Glyph: ⇡
Move: unfold compressed structure back into richer detail
Function: rehydration, explanation, simulation
Tensor signature: (token, context, reconstructed_form)

What it does

Turns:
	•	one phrase into a framework
	•	one equation into a world
	•	one image into a doctrine

Martial instruction

Unroll the banner only when the room is ready to see it.

Use when

You have a compact symbol but need operational detail.

Failure mode

Hallucinated detail beyond the original invariant.

⸻

6. Split

Glyph: ⋈
Move: separate one thing into components
Function: factorization, decomposition, disentangling
Tensor signature: (whole, components, coupling_terms)

What it does

Separates:
	•	signal from noise
	•	cost from price
	•	state from trait
	•	meaning from wording
	•	actor from role

Martial instruction

Take the braided rope apart strand by strand.

Use when

The system is tangled and you need levers.

Failure mode

Breaking what only works as a whole.

⸻

7. Bind

Glyph: ⊗
Move: combine multiple components into a higher-order unit
Function: composition, coupling, fusion
Tensor signature: (a, b, interaction_rule, product)

What it does

Creates:
	•	systems
	•	compounds
	•	metaphors
	•	institutions
	•	tensor products
	•	narrative molecules

Martial instruction

Join hand, breath, and timing into one strike.

Use when

Separate parts are weak but together form a useful object.

Failure mode

Forcing incompatible things into brittle union.

⸻

8. Filter

Glyph: ⫽
Move: keep some structure, discard the rest
Function: selection, projection, denoising, ethics gate
Tensor signature: (input, criterion, retained_subspace)

What it does

Lets through:
	•	useful signals
	•	safe moves
	•	relevant features
	•	admissible interpretations

Martial instruction

Do not fight every arrow. Let the bad ones pass into the sand.

Use when

The environment is noisy or adversarial.

Failure mode

Filtering out the anomaly that mattered.

⸻

9. Lift

Glyph: ⤴
Move: move a structure to a higher-order space where it becomes easier
Function: abstraction, embedding, extension
Tensor signature: (object, higher_space, gained_freedom)

What it does

Turns:
	•	a hard problem into a geometry problem
	•	a local issue into a systems issue
	•	a concrete example into a general theorem

Martial instruction

Step to higher ground; the maze becomes a map.

Use when

You are trapped in local detail or zero-sum framing.

Failure mode

Floating so high you lose operational contact.

⸻

10. Project

Glyph: ⤵
Move: bring a higher structure back into usable concrete form
Function: implementation, instantiation, embodiment
Tensor signature: (abstract_form, substrate, practical_output)

What it does

Converts:
	•	theorem into algorithm
	•	principle into checklist
	•	strategy into next action
	•	architecture into module

Martial instruction

A stance means nothing until it touches the ground.

Use when

You have a good abstraction but no execution handle.

Failure mode

Oversimplifying and losing the governing invariant.

⸻

11. Flow

Glyph: ~>
Move: track how a system evolves under repeated transformation
Function: dynamics, process, iteration, diffusion
Tensor signature: (state_t, operator, state_t+1)

What it does

Models:
	•	learning
	•	decay
	•	spread
	•	convergence
	•	drift
	•	feedback loops

Martial instruction

Do not study the punch frozen in air; study the path it traces.

Use when

The shape of change matters more than the static snapshot.

Failure mode

Assuming stable flow where thresholds or shocks dominate.

⸻

12. Lock / Invariant

Glyph: ⊙
Move: identify what does not change through transformation
Function: conservation, identity, truth-rail
Tensor signature: (transform_set, preserved_quantity)

What it does

Finds:
	•	conserved structure
	•	stable ratios
	•	ethical rails
	•	identity across change
	•	the “same thing” across forms

Martial instruction

In every motion, keep one point still.

Use when

You need trust, continuity, or transfer across domains.

Failure mode

Treating a temporary regularity as eternal law.

