Part V — Martial Arts Instruction Manual

How to use the forms

This is the practical part.

⸻

White Belt: Recognition

Goal: see patterns without forcing them.

Practice:
	•	Name the system
	•	Name the domain
	•	Ask which move is present already

Questions:
	•	Is this mostly a Map, Split, or Flow problem?
	•	What is changing?
	•	What is staying fixed?

Rule:
Do not attack before you can name the stance.

⸻

Yellow Belt: Single-Move Application

Goal: solve problems with one transformation at a time.

Examples:
	•	stuck in detail → Lift
	•	too abstract → Project
	•	overwhelmed → Filter
	•	tangled issue → Split
	•	need summary → Compress

Rule:
One clean move beats five muddy ones.

⸻

Green Belt: Combination Forms

Goal: chain two or three transformations.

Examples:
	•	Split → Filter → Bind
Untangle parts, keep the useful ones, recombine
	•	Map → Mirror → Lock
Translate across domains, reverse the view, locate the invariant
	•	Lift → Rotate → Project
Abstract upward, reframe, return with an action

Rule:
The second move should answer the weakness of the first.

⸻

Blue Belt: Cross-Domain Combat

Goal: use one field to solve another.

Method:
	1.	choose source domain
	2.	identify invariant pattern
	3.	map only preserved structure
	4.	test where analogy breaks
	5.	project into target domain

Example:
Market problem as fluid dynamics:
	•	bottlenecks
	•	pressure differentials
	•	leak paths
	•	resistance
	•	reservoirs

Rule:
Borrow the skeleton, not the skin.

⸻

Brown Belt: Opponent Study

Goal: analyze confusion, contradiction, and misdirection.

Use:
	•	Mirror for hidden assumptions
	•	Invert for reverse causality
	•	Null for missing variable
	•	Threshold for sudden behavior changes
	•	Relay for multi-angle confirmation

Rule:
Most confusion is an unmarked transformation.

⸻

Black Belt: Invariant Combat

Goal: move freely through forms without losing truth.

At this level:
	•	every metaphor is tested
	•	every abstraction must project back down
	•	every compression must rehydrate
	•	every system must reveal its invariants

Rule:
Mastery is not having many moves. Mastery is preserving the invariant through all moves.

